AB  - 12-step (TS) attendance predicts increased abstinence among alcohol dependent individuals (Emrick et al., 1993), and abstinence-based social support is a significant factor accounting for the salutary eects of TS programs (Bond et al., 2003; Kelly et al., 2011). Few studies have examined the eect of TS attendance in dually-diagnosed individuals (DD) or the specific benefit of social support for DD attending TS programs. This study examined whether DD assigned to TS facilitation treatment (TSF) had greater gains in abstinence-based support than did those assigned to treatment-asusual (TAU).We also examined whether type of diagnosis (bipolar, depression, or psychosis) interacted with treatment type to predict abstinence-based social support. Participants were 121 DD individuals with an alcohol use disorder and either bipolar disorder (n = 43), depression (n = 56), or psychotic disorder (n = 22). Individuals were not excluded for illicit drug use, and 73.3%reported using drugs on an average of 42.8 of the 90 days before baseline. Participants were randomized to TAU plus 12 weekly sessions of TSF (n = 83) or TAUalone (n = 38) and completed assessments at 3, 6, 9, and 12 months post-treatment. The Important People and Activities inventory (IPA; Longabaugh et al., 1993) measured social networks, and the Form 90 (Miller, 1996) measured alcohol use. Analyses of variance tested whether abstinence-based social support diered as a function of diagnosis and treatment type. Measures of abstinence-based support consisted of an average of responses on the IPA in the 3, 6, 9, and 12 month assessments. Results showed that, relative to individuals in TAU, those in TSF had a greater proportion of friends in recovery and more support for coming to treatment. Participants with bipolar and depressive disorders reported more general social support and support for coming to treatment relative to those with psychotic disorders. Treatment type and diagnosis did not interact to predict overall abstinence-based social support. Post-hoc analyses showed that neither proportion of friends in recovery nor support for treatment were related to percent days abstinent (PDA) from alcohol at follow-up. However, general social support did correlate with greater PDA during follow-up. Results suggest that TSF may mobilize abstinence-based social supportmore than TAU for DD individuals, consistent with the literature on changemechanisms in non-dually diagnosed 12-step participants
