AB  - The current project examined the psychometric properties of an understudied assessment tool related to twelve-step group affiliation. In the first study, 184 substance dependent individuals consecutively admitted to a sober house completed the TSPQ and several relevant questionnaires. Participants had an average age of 40 years, were fairly ethnically diverse (67% white), with the majority identifying as male (72%). The TSPQ data was analyzed with exploratory factor analyses with oblique rotation, with a 3-factor model providing the best fit (RMSEA = 0.03), accounting for 47% of the variance. The three factors reflected different degrees of affiliation (Active Engagement, Active Affiliation, and Passive Affiliation) and had different patterns of correlation to measures of lifetime substance use (CAGE-AID, ASUS-Involvement), consequences due to substance use (ASUS-Disruption), and motivation to change (ASUS-Motivation to change). Further, Active Engagement predicted successful discharge from a sober house (Wald = 5.09, p < 0.05, Exp(B) = 3.34). In the second study, 219 current or former members of AA were recruited online to complete the TSPQ and several different questionnaires to further validate the factors identified in study 1. The sample was equivalent on gender (55% female), with an average age of 40 years, and 82% of the sample self-identified as White. The three factors were varyingly correlated with each other. In addition, a series of multiple regression analyses suggested that the TSPQ subscales were differentially predictive of subjective sense of well being (SWLS), extent of alcohol abuse issues (MAST), and motivation to change (SOCRATES-Recognition and SOCRATES-Taking steps). Overall, the results suggest that the TSPQ is tapping three categories of twelve-step group activity, and that affiliation can be defined in terms of different types of involvement. It appears that individuals may demonstrate a variety of attitudes and behaviors, both active and passive, that are differentially associated with established correlates of substance use consequences, motivation for change, and successful treatment outcomes. It is hoped that the TSPQ can be used to gauge level of twelve-step affiliation among treatment clients and counselors can utilize this information strategically in treatment planning to more directly tailor services and referrals
