AB  - A relatively new research strategy conceptualizes process as intermediate or "micro"-outcomes. These interim behavioral targets of specific components or phases of therapy serve a dual role-they are the behavioral goals or outcomes of therapy components and they are also the key ingredients of behavioral change responsible for more traditional outcome variables (e.g., drug use). This little-researched 'micro-outcomes' process research strategy was explored within the context of a clinical trial comparing methadone maintenance enhanced with Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT) or Intensive Twelve-Step Facilitation (ITSF) to a control condition (methadone maintenance) among polysubstance-abusing methadone clients. The primary dependent variables were problematic opiate and other drug use, as established by urinalysis. A Processes of Change Measure (PCM) was developed specifically to measure client "micro-outcomes". Study hypotheses primarily focused on two goals-to identify the specific processes responsible for differences in drug use across conditions (e.g., both ACT and ITSF subjects showed significantly lower total drug use, as measured by urinalysis, than did the methadone only condition) and to evaluate the performance of the PCM, and by extension, the micro-outcomes methodology. Despite some notable shortcomings, the PCM performed as well or outperformed traditional measures in explaining differential performance in treatment outcome, and in a range of functions of assessment utility, including the ability to predict successful and non-successful subjects. Using descriptive behavioral processes (micro-outcomes), based on their face validity with important therapeutic processes, offers promise as a means of conducting process research. Significant time and financial resources were saved by not studying process through more traditional methods, such as coding important moments in videotaped sessions and correlating these with outcome. Despite differences in historical development and foundational theory of substance abuse, ACT and 12-Step were similar in several areas of process. Consequently, enhancing 12-Step treatment with compatible process components from ACT (i.e., psychological acceptance and believability) may improve the effectiveness of the 12-Step model. In addition, the theoretically built-up processes associated with ACT may provide 12-Step programs with a stronger link to the broad base of psychological knowledge and the scientific method. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)
