AB  - Participation in12-step mutual help organizations (MHOs) is often prescribed during treatment for young adults (i.e., ages 18-24 yrs) with substance use disorders (SUD) to foster continued remission. The Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) 2011 Membership Survey found, however, that the average age ofmembers was 49 yrs, with only 13%under age 30. Given that engagement in 12-stepMHOs is related to perceived similarities amongmembers, this older age composition may serve as a barrier to young adult participation. This study examined the relationships among age composition of 12-step groups, young adult participation, and alcohol/drug use outcome. Young adults (N = 296; 18-24 yrs) enrolled in a naturalistic study of residential treatment eectiveness were assessed at intake, 3, 6, and 12 months on 12-step attendance, age composition of attended 12-step groups (participants were asked to report the extent to which members of meetings they attended most often were about their age; response options were coded ordinally as: "none," "some," "about half," "most," or "all"; [Kelly et al., 2011]), and treatment outcome (Percent Days Abstinent [PDA]). Hierarchical linear models (HLM) tested the relation of age composition to PDA concurrently and in subsequent follow-ups, controlling for confounds. To determine if age composition conferred a unique recovery benefit beyond that of attendance, attendance and age composition were tested in the samemodel. The proportion attending AA meetings at intake, 3-, 6-, and 12-month follow-up were 6%, 38%, 33%, and 27%, respectively. At each follow-up, 34%, 30%, and 28%of patients, respectively, reported that at least "some" of the AA groupmembers were young adults. Results fromcontemporaneous and lagged HLM analyses found that more similar age composition at each time point was related to greater PDA (ps<0.05). HLMs testing the unique eect of age composition over and above attendance found that age composition was unrelated to PDA in contemporaneousmodels (b = 0.22, p = 0.09), but in laggedmodels it was (b = 0.41, p = 0.04); the age composition by time interaction was not significant (b = -0.51, p = 0.07). Among young adult AA attendees, age composition of attended meetings may be an important variable that confers additional recovery benefits independent of frequency of attendance. Age composition should be considered when prescribing participation in MHOs to young adults in order to maximize potential recovery benefis
