AB  - Purpose: Research on the benefits derived from 12-step mutual help participation among individuals with alcohol use disorder has increased substantially in quantity and quality during the past 15 years. This has been facilitated by a variety of measures that have emerged to assess 12-step experience. However, existing measures typically clump and summarize experiences from very different 12-step fellowships (e.g., Alcoholics Anonymous, Cocaine Anonymous, Narcotics Anonymous) into a single metric and frequently succeed in capturing only a narrow range of 12-step-related experience. Here we report the results from the development and use of a comprehensive multidimensional measure of 12-step mutual-help group experience. Methods: Items were constructed using existing scientific literature, relevant expert consensus, and current 12-step participants, to develop items that captured the full range of 12-step experience. Two clinical samples of young adults and adolescents (n = 430) were administered the instrument at multiple time points prospectively. An additional one week testretest reliability check was conducted on a subsample. Results: Results indicated high content validity and excellent reliability across seven major dimensions of 12-step experience (meeting attendance, meeting participation, fellowship involvement, step work, mandated attendance, subjective affiliation, and safety) and the measure successfully discriminated between anticipated levels of 12-step involvement between samples. Conclusion: This measure may facilitate much greater insight into the dynamic nature and range of activities engaged in by individuals with alcohol use disorder across various 12-step organizations
