AB  - Purpose: Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) and Narcotics Anonymous (NA) have proven to be costeffective recovery resources for adults and also appear helpful for youth. However, anecdotal concerns about adolescents' safety at meetings have dampened enthusiasm regarding youth AA/NA participation among some programs and clinicians. Unfortunately, little information exists to evaluate such concerns. To this end, the current study sought examine issues of safety at AA and NA meetings among adolescents treated in an outpatient setting for substance use disorder. Method: Outpatients (n = 127; 24% female) were assessed at intake, and 3, 6, and 12 months regarding perceived safety at AA/NA, experience of negative incidents, reasons for liking or disliking AA/NA, and reasons for nonattendance/discontinuation. Results: By 12-month follow-up, 57.5% reported some AA/NA attendance with a combined lifetime exposure of 5,340 meetings. Of these, 21.9% reported at least one negative experience, which was more common among NA than AA attendees. Overall, youth reported feeling very safe at meetings and ratings did not differ by age or gender. Reasons for discontinuation or nonattendance were unrelated to safety or negative incidents. Conclusions: Weighing risks against documented benefits, these preliminary findings suggest referral to AA/NA should not be discouraged, but, similar to adults, youth experiences at meetings should be monitored
