AB  - Introduction: With a sample of adolescents who entered substance use treatment in a private, non-profit integrated health care delivery system, this study examined patterns of primary care (PC) and substance use treatment services as they relate to outcomes over 7 years, and developed a model of continuing care. Methods: Study subjects were 419 adolescents, aged 13-18, recruited at four Kaiser Permanente Northern California substance use treatment programs between 2000 and 2002. Follow-up interviews were conducted at 6 months, 1, 3, 5, and 7 years after treatment entry. Measures at follow-ups included alcohol and drug use, twelve-step participation, and posttreatment service utilization. Results: The final sample was 34% female, 49% white, with mean age of 16.1 years at treatment entry. A total of 305 (73%) started substance use treatment. Only 30%, 19% and 15% had additional substance use treatment services during years 1-3, 3-5, and 5-7, respectively. Mixed-effects logistic random intercept models indicated that having substance use treatment based on need and having routine PC visits were associated with better outcomes over time. Compared with those who had no treatment need and received no substance use treatment, adolescents who had treatment need but did not receive it were 72% less likely, whereas those who had treatment need and did receive it were 14% more likely, to be abstinent from drugs at follow-ups (ORs=0.28 and 1.14, respectively). Similarly, there was a significant interaction between treatment need and receiving substance use treatment on risky drinking over time. Furthermore, having PC visits was associated with drug abstinence over time (OR=1.83, p=0.0185). Twelve-step participation was associated with higher odds of being abstinent from alcohol and drugs, and lower odds of risky drinking, across time points (ORs=3.70, 3.74 and 0.46, respectively; all p<0.01). We developed a measure of "continuing care" at each time point that takes into account receiving routine PC, substance use treatment based on need and twelve-step participation, and found significant associations between receiving continuing care and better substance use outcomes over 7 years. Conclusion: Continuing care that includes collaborative PC and specialty care management to support ongoing monitoring, self-care and treatment as needed is important for long-term recovery of adolescent substance use patients
