AB  - Veterans have been found to be twice as likely to die of suicide compared to nonveterans in the general population. Veterans with comorbid alcohol/substance use disorders (ASUD) and depression may be at greater risk for suicide than veterans without these disorders. This study examined the temporal relationship between severity of suicidal ideation (SI) and alcohol and other substance use (ASU) over an 18-month clinical trial, utilizing dynamic latent difference score (LDS) modeling. The trial used Integrative Cognitive Behavioral Therapy and 12-Step Facilitation Therapy and consisted of 6 months of group psychotherapy and an additional 12-month follow-up phase. Interviews occurred at pretreatment and quarterly thereafter (approximately every 3 months). Three repeated measures of SI (Beck Depression Inventory question #9, Hamilton Depression Rating Scale question #22, and the Addiction Severity Index question #P8) served as observed indicator variables for the latent SI variable. A binary ASU variable (0=no use, 1=use) was developed for each 3-month assessment period using the Timeline Follow Back. The sample consisted of 236 predominantly male (88%) veterans (mean age 49) meeting DSM-IV criteria for alcohol, cannabis, and/or stimulant dependence and major depressive disorder. Univariate LDS structural equation models established a longitudinal change model of SI. A nonlinear change model, with a negative linear slope and a slightly positive quadratic slope, provided good fit to the data, v2(25, n = 222) = 37.02; CFI = 0.97; RMSEA = 0.05. This model of change suggests that individuals initially show a greater decrease in SI severity relative to the later time points. This suggests that change in SI severity is more pronounced during treatment and plateaus during follow-up. Next, the ASU variable was added as a time-varying predictor of longitudinal change in SI. This model also fit the data adequately, v2(60, n = 223) = 100.94; CFI = 0.89; RMSEA = 0.06. Results suggest that individuals with any alcohol and other substance use within the assessment period have a significant increase (b = 0.243, p < 0.05) in SI severity within that period. Findings suggest that among individuals with comorbid ASUD and depression, across time, any substance use increases SI severity. Consequently, it may be beneficial for clinicians to monitor and manage (i.e. safety planning) SI among patients with comorbid ASUD and depression who relapse to prevent escalation of SI and self-harm behaviors
